{"title_page": "Midrasha", "text_new": "A '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') is an institute of [[Torah study]] for women, generally in [[Israel]]. It is typically an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] institution that caters solely to women, and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. An alternative term, and translation, is '[[seminary]]' ({{hebrew|\u05e1\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e8}}). <ref name=\"science.co.il\">[https://www.science.co.il/jewish-studies/Midrashot.php ''Midrashot''], science.co.il</ref>\nA midrasha that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' ({{hebrew|\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df}}, institute).\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\"''Midrasha''\" is often associated with Religious Zionist institutions, while \"Seminary\" refers to ''[[Haredi]]'' institutions.\nThe term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used  more widely, referring to [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], institutions.\n\n==Structure==\n===Curriculum===\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. \n<ref name=\"Lilith\">[https://www.lilith.org/blog/2014/09/a-modest-year-in-israel-when-young-women-go-to-seminary/ A Modest Year in Israel: When Young Women go to \u201cSeminary\u201d]. [[Lilith (magazine)|''Lilith'']], 2014 </ref>\nAll cover [[Tanakh]] (Hebrew Bible), [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Halacha|Jewish law]]  and [[Musar Literature|Musar (Ethics)]] / [[Hasidic philosophy|''Hasidus'']].<ref name=\"science.co.il\"/> See [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]] for the general content of each topic. \nDepending on the institution's stance, the weight and role assigned to Talmud particularly, and in fact to textual-skills generally, will differ re men's yeshivot, and between ''midrashot''.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n\n[[Religious Zionist]] and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' include the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]]'s [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]], sister school of [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]].\nTreatment of Tanakh and Jewish philosophy, often referred to here as [[Jewish thought|''Machshava'']],  will typically be text-focused, built around [[chavruta]]-based study as at yeshivot;<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\nthis entails paired-study where assigned sources are prepared for ''[[shiur]]'', a lecture delivered as a discursive-review.\nAt some institutions, [[Talmud]] is studied directly, also as at men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}}, if less intensively\n(see [[Women in Judaism #Joseph Solovetchik]]).\nRegardless, Jewish law will generally be studied with ''practice'' in view: i.e., as opposed to [[Yeshiva#Jewish_law|at a men's Yeshiva]], where the derivation is from Talmudic sources through codification \n(At [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]], [[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] and [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] the treatment is Talmud-based;\nsee also [[Drisha Institute]].<ref>[https://www.drisha.co.il/ drisha.co.il]: \"\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e0\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d5\u05ea \u05dc\u05d4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05dc\u05d2\u05d3\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4\"</ref>)\n\nThe [[Haredi]] aligned seminaries - for example [[Beth Jacob Jerusalem]] - are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]].\n(Today, ''Beis Yaakov'' refers to high school, while \"Seminary\" is used for a post-high school institution.)\nSeminaries are typically more conservative in their approach than ''Midrashot'':\nselections from the Talmud may be studied, but only in the context of other classes, especially philosophy and Musar; \nthese institutions then also assign less weight to textual skills,<ref name=\"Lilith\"/> with content delivered primarily via lecture.\n(See [[Bais Yaakov #Curriculum]], [[Women in Judaism #Yisrael Meir Kagan]].)\n[[Bais_Yaakov#Hasidic_schools|Hasidic-aligned institutions]], for example [[Beth Rivkah]], are similarly positioned; their curricula differ in that they emphasize the works of their respective [[Rebbe]]. \nHaredi and Hasidic schools typically also emphasize [[Hashkafa#Gender_roles|the role of women in Torah]], covering topics such as [[Tzniut]] (modesty), [[Shalom Bayit]] (\"domestic peace\") and [[Chinuch]] (education of one's children), with these classes focusing on ''values'', as opposed to sources. <ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n\nMany diaspora-based Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'', or \u201csem\u201d, in Israel for a year or more following high school; \nseveral ''midrashot'' and seminaries offer special programs, for example ''Shana Ba'aretz'' at Nishmat, or  the \"Overseas Program\" at [[Midreshet HaRova]].\nAdditional to Torah study, these usually include <ref name=\"Lilith\"/> [[Tourism_in_Israel|touring of Israel]], [[Shabbaton]]s in various communities, and often volunteer work in local schools and hospitals, and seminars with journalists and politicians.\nSome institutions accommodate  [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]] with similar year-programs, designed to build knowledge and skills; well known are [[Neve Yerushalayim]], [[Mayanot]], and [[Machon Roni]].\n\n===Certifications===\nIn the Religious Zionist community women often continue their studies at one of the midrasha-affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]], which offer a Torah-program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree; \n([[masters degree|masters' level]]) specializations are often offered in ''Tanakh''  or Jewish philosophy. \n[[Bar-Ilan University]] operates a ''midrasha'', and students in all disciplines may then continue Torah study in parallel with their academic studies (with a requirement of at least seven courses in Judaism<ref>[https://midrasha.biu.ac.il/en/node/406 Bar-Ilan ''Midrasha'']</ref>).\n[[Machon Tal]], associated with JCT, the [[Jerusalem College of Technology]], similarly offers degrees in engineering or management. \n\nMost Haredi and Hasidic seminaries likewise offer certificates, and sometimes degrees, in Education. The two year certificates are through the [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d9\u05d8\u05d4 \u05e1\u05d0\u05dc\u05d3 |Szold Institute]], and are recognized by the [[Israel Ministry of Education]] as equivalent to the [[bagrut|national matriculation]].<ref>[https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/1395928/ministry-education-recognizes-teaching-certificates-matriculation-paves-way-charedi-women-pursue-college-israel.html discussion in the theyeshivaworld.com]</ref>\n[[Jerusalem_College_of_Technology#Branches|JCT's Lustig Campus]] in [[Ramat Gan]] hosts degree programs for Haredi and Hasidic women;\nsee also [[The Haredi Campus - The Academic College Ono]].\n\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges; see [[Yeshiva #College credit]]. \nSome ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously.\nThe Modern Orthodox [[Stern College for Women]] - in Manhattan, New York - combines Torah and University studies, as at Bar-Ilan;\nthe Haredi [[Touro_College_and_University_System#Undergraduate_schools|Lander College for Women]] similarly.\n\n==Other Programs==\nAs above, the term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used for [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], institutions. These are usually structured around continuing / [[adult education]], and accept both men and women. Examples are \nthe Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Ein Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel, \nand the [[Florence Melton#Melton Schools|Melton School]]'s ''Midrasha'' in [[Cape Town]]. <ref>[https://meltoncapetown.org/midrasha/ Midrasha Adult Education Institute], meltoncapetown.org</ref>\n\nWithin the Orthodox community, programs of this type are also offered, \nfor example by  [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]] <ref>[https://www.matan.org.il/en/learn-en/lessons/ Classes], matan.org.il</ref>\nand ''Emunah''; <ref>[http://www.emunah.org.il/%d7%90%d7%9e%d7%95%d7%a0%d7%94-%d7%91%d7%a7%d7%94%d7%99%d7%9c%d7%94/%d7%91%d7%aa%d7%99-%d7%9e%d7%93%d7%a8%d7%a9/ \u05d1\u05ea\u05d9-\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9], emunah.org.il; with international branches, for example [http://emunah.co.za/ emunah.co.za]</ref>\nthese are limited to women.\nMany synagogues host a [[Kollel#Community_kollelim|\"Community kollel\"]], which has a similar function, and offers adult education to both men and women (usually separately).\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term ''Midrasha'' is also used for programs where high school students can continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]]. <ref>[https://www.midrasha.org/ midrasha.org]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[List of Midrashot]] & [[List of yeshivas, midrashas and Hebrew schools in Israel #Midrashas]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n* [[Ulpana]]\n* [[Women in Judaism]] and esp. [[Women in Judaism #Views on the education of women|#Views on the education of women]]\n* [[Jewish education #Girls' education]]  \n* [[Hashkafa #Gender roles]]\n* [[Orthodox Judaism #Diversity]]\n* [[Religious Zionism #Educational institutions]]\n* [[Haredi Judaism #Education]]\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "text_old": "A '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') is an institute of [[Torah study]] for women, generally in [[Israel]]. It is typically an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] institution that caters solely to women, and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. An alternative term, and translation, is '[[seminary]]' ({{hebrew|\u05e1\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e8}}). <ref name=\"science.co.il\">[https://www.science.co.il/jewish-studies/Midrashot.php ''Midrashot''], science.co.il</ref>\nA midrasha that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' ({{hebrew|\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df}}, institute).\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\"''Midrasha''\" is often associated with Religious Zionist institutions, while \"Seminary\" refers to ''[[Haredi]]'' institutions.\nThe term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used  more widely, referring to [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], institutions.\n\n==Structure==\n===Curriculum===\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. \n<ref name=\"Lilith\">[https://www.lilith.org/blog/2014/09/a-modest-year-in-israel-when-young-women-go-to-seminary/ A Modest Year in Israel: When Young Women go to \u201cSeminary\u201d]. [[Lilith (magazine)|''Lilith'']], 2014 </ref>\nAll cover [[Tanakh]] (Hebrew Bible), [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Halacha|Jewish law]]  and [[Musar Literature|Musar (Ethics)]] / [[Hasidic philosophy|''Hasidus'']].<ref name=\"science.co.il\"/> See [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]] for the general content of each topic. \nDepending on the institution's stance, the weight and role assigned to Talmud particularly, and in fact to textual-skills generally, will differ re men's yeshivot, and between ''midrashot''.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n\n[[Religious Zionist]] and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' include the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]]'s [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]], sister school of [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]].\nTreatment of Tanakh and Jewish philosophy, often referred to here as [[Jewish thought|''Machshava'']],  will typically be text-focused, built around [[chavruta]]-based study as at yeshivot;<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\nthis entails paired-study where assigned sources are prepared for ''[[shiur]]'', a lecture delivered as a discursive-review.\nAt some institutions, [[Talmud]] is studied directly, also as at men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}}, if less intensively\n(see [[Women in Judaism #Joseph Solovetchik]]).\nRegardless, Jewish law will generally be studied with ''practice'' in view: i.e., as opposed to [[Yeshiva#Jewish_law|at a men's Yeshiva]], where the derivation is from Talmudic sources through codification \n(At [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]], [[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] and [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] the treatment is Talmud-based;\nsee also [[Drisha Institute]].<ref>[https://www.drisha.co.il/ drisha.co.il]: \"\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e0\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d5\u05ea \u05dc\u05d4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05dc\u05d2\u05d3\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4\"</ref>)\n\nThe [[Haredi]] aligned seminaries - for example [[Beth Jacob Jerusalem]] - are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]].\n(Today, ''Beis Yaakov'' refers to high school, while \"Seminary\" is used for a post-high school institution.)\nThese are typically more conservative in their approach:\nselections from the Talmud may be studied, but only in the context of other classes, especially philosophy and Musar; \nthese institutions then also assign less weight to textual skills,<ref name=\"Lilith\"/> with content delivered primarily via lecture.\n(See [[Bais Yaakov #Curriculum]], [[Women in Judaism #Yisrael Meir Kagan]].)\n[[Bais_Yaakov#Hasidic_schools|Hasidic-aligned institutions]], for example [[Beth Rivkah]], are similarly positioned; their curricula differ in that they emphasize the works of their respective [[Rebbe]]. \nHaredi and Hasidic schools typically also emphasize [[Hashkafa#Gender_roles|the role of women in Torah]], covering topics such as [[Tzniut]] (modesty), [[Shalom Bayit]] (\"domestic peace\") and [[Chinuch]] (education of one's children), with these classes focusing on ''values'', as opposed to sources. <ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n\nMany diaspora-based Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'', or \u201csem\u201d, in Israel for a year or more following high school; \nseveral ''midrashot'' and seminaries offer special programs, for example ''Shana Ba'aretz'' at Nishmat, or  the \"Overseas Program\" at [[Midreshet HaRova]].\nAdditional to Torah study, these usually include <ref name=\"Lilith\"/> [[Tourism_in_Israel|touring of Israel]], [[Shabbaton]]s in various communities, and often volunteer work in local schools and hospitals, and seminars with journalists and politicians.\nSome institutions accommodate  [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]] with similar year-programs, designed to build knowledge and skills; well known are [[Neve Yerushalayim]], [[Mayanot]], and [[Machon Roni]].\n\n===Certifications===\nIn the Religious Zionist community women often continue their studies at one of the midrasha-affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]], which offer a Torah-program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree; \n([[masters degree|masters' level]]) specializations are often offered in ''Tanakh''  or Jewish philosophy. \n[[Bar-Ilan University]] operates a ''midrasha'', and students in all disciplines may then continue Torah study in parallel with their academic studies (with a requirement of at least seven courses in Judaism<ref>[https://midrasha.biu.ac.il/en/node/406 Bar-Ilan ''Midrasha'']</ref>).\n[[Machon Tal]], associated with JCT, the [[Jerusalem College of Technology]], similarly offers degrees in engineering or management. \n\nMost Haredi and Hasidic seminaries likewise offer certificates, and sometimes degrees, in Education. The two year certificates are through the [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d9\u05d8\u05d4 \u05e1\u05d0\u05dc\u05d3 |Szold Institute]], and are recognized by the [[Israel Ministry of Education]] as equivalent to the [[bagrut|national matriculation]].<ref>[https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/1395928/ministry-education-recognizes-teaching-certificates-matriculation-paves-way-charedi-women-pursue-college-israel.html discussion in the theyeshivaworld.com]</ref>\n[[Jerusalem_College_of_Technology#Branches|JCT's Lustig Campus]] in [[Ramat Gan]] hosts degree programs for Haredi and Hasidic women;\nsee also [[The Haredi Campus - The Academic College Ono]].\n\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges; see [[Yeshiva #College credit]]. \nSome ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously.\nThe Modern Orthodox [[Stern College for Women]] - in Manhattan, New York - combines Torah and University studies, as at Bar-Ilan;\nthe Haredi [[Touro_College_and_University_System#Undergraduate_schools|Lander College for Women]] similarly.\n\n==Other Programs==\nAs above, the term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used for [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], institutions. These are usually structured around continuing / [[adult education]], and accept both men and women. Examples are \nthe Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Ein Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel, \nand the [[Florence Melton#Melton Schools|Melton School]]'s ''Midrasha'' in [[Cape Town]]. <ref>[https://meltoncapetown.org/midrasha/ Midrasha Adult Education Institute], meltoncapetown.org</ref>\n\nWithin the Orthodox community, programs of this type are also offered, \nfor example by  [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]] <ref>[https://www.matan.org.il/en/learn-en/lessons/ Classes], matan.org.il</ref>\nand ''Emunah''; <ref>[http://www.emunah.org.il/%d7%90%d7%9e%d7%95%d7%a0%d7%94-%d7%91%d7%a7%d7%94%d7%99%d7%9c%d7%94/%d7%91%d7%aa%d7%99-%d7%9e%d7%93%d7%a8%d7%a9/ \u05d1\u05ea\u05d9-\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9], emunah.org.il; with international branches, for example [http://emunah.co.za/ emunah.co.za]</ref>\nthese are limited to women.\nMany synagogues host a [[Kollel#Community_kollelim|\"Community kollel\"]], which has a similar function, and offers adult education to both men and women (usually separately).\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term ''Midrasha'' is also used for programs where high school students can continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]]. <ref>[https://www.midrasha.org/ midrasha.org]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[List of Midrashot]] & [[List of yeshivas, midrashas and Hebrew schools in Israel #Midrashas]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n* [[Ulpana]]\n* [[Women in Judaism]] and esp. [[Women in Judaism #Views on the education of women|#Views on the education of women]]\n* [[Jewish education #Girls' education]]  \n* [[Hashkafa #Gender roles]]\n* [[Orthodox Judaism #Diversity]]\n* [[Religious Zionism #Educational institutions]]\n* [[Haredi Judaism #Education]]\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midrasha"}
{"title_page": "Better Call Saul", "text_new": "{{about|the television series|the ''Breaking Bad'' episode|Better Call Saul (Breaking Bad)|the ''Homeland'' episode|Better Call Saul (Homeland)}}\n{{short description|American crime drama television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Better Call Saul\n| image                    = Better Call Saul logo.svg\n| alt                      = Text \"Better Call Saul\" with drawn set of balance scales to the right\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Crime drama]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/01/21/better-call-saul |title=Better Call Saul |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=Jeff |last=Jensen |date=January 28, 2015 |accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Black comedy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/reviews/tv-review-better-call-saul-1201409820/ |title=TV Review: 'Better Call Saul' |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=January 21, 2015 |accessdate=April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Tragedy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/better-call-saul-evolution-season-4-vince-gilligan-breaking-bad/ |title=Better Call Saul Has Evolved Into One of TV's Greatest Tragedies |work=TV Guide |first=Kaitlin |last=Thomas |date=August 2, 2018 |accessdate=August 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Legal drama]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/better-call-saul-is-finally-becoming-breaking-bad |title=Better Call Saul Is Finally Becoming Breaking Bad |work=GQ |first=Scott |last=Meslow |date=April 10, 2017 |accessdate=November 21, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Vince Gilligan]]\n* [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bob Odenkirk]]\n* [[Jonathan Banks]]\n* [[Rhea Seehorn]]\n* [[Patrick Fabian]]\n* [[Michael Mando]]\n* [[Michael McKean]]\n* [[Giancarlo Esposito]]\n* [[Tony Dalton]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Little Barrie]]\n| composer                 = [[Dave Porter (composer)|Dave Porter]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 5\n| num_episodes             = 50\n| list_episodes            = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Vince Gilligan\n* Peter Gould\n* [[Mark Johnson (producer)|Mark Johnson]]\n* Melissa Bernstein\n* [[Thomas Schnauz]]\n* [[Gennifer Hutchison]]}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Bob Odenkirk\n* Nina Jack\n* Diane Mercer\n* Robin Sweet\n* [[Gordon Smith (screenwriter)|Gordon Smith]]\n* [[Jonathan Glatzer]]}}\n| location                 = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico|Albuquerque]], [[New Mexico]]\n| cinematography           = [[Arthur Albert]]<br />Marshall Adams\n| runtime                  = 41\u201360 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* High Bridge Productions\n* Crystal Diner Productions\n* Gran Via Productions\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]}}\n| distributor              = Sony Pictures Television\n| network                  = [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[1080i]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n* [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])}}\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital|5.1]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|2|8}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = ''[[Breaking Bad]]''\n| related                  = ''[[Talking Saul]]''\n| website                  = http://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul\n| image_size               = 250\n| production_website       = https://www.sonypictures.com/tv/bettercallsaul\n}}\n\n'''''Better Call Saul''''' is an American television [[crime drama]] series created by [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]], and a prequel and spin-off of Gilligan's prior series ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. Set in the early to mid [[2000s (decade)|2000s]], the series follows the story of con-man turned small-time lawyer Jimmy McGill ([[Bob Odenkirk]]), beginning six years before the events of ''Breaking Bad'' and showing his transformation into the persona of criminal for hire [[Saul Goodman]]. McGill becomes the lawyer for former police officer [[Mike Ehrmantraut]] ([[Jonathan Banks]]), whose skills allow him to enter the criminal underworld of drug trafficking in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]. The show premiered on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] on February 8, 2015, airing five seasons to date. A sixth and final season is scheduled to air in 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last=Thorne |first=Will |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/better-call-saul-renewed-final-season-1203470181/ |title='Better Call Saul' Renewed for 6th and Final Season at AMC |work=Variety |date=January 16, 2020 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcGill is initially working as a low-paid lawyer with the back room of a nail salon as his home and office. His friend and romantic interest [[Kim Wexler]] ([[Rhea Seehorn]]) works as a lawyer at the firm of Hamlin, Hamlin & McGill (HHM), where she and Jimmy once worked in the mailroom. Partners at HHM include Jimmy's nemesis [[Howard Hamlin]] ([[Patrick Fabian]]) and his brother [[Chuck McGill]] ([[Michael McKean]]). Ehrmantraut conducts illegal drug distribution with [[Nacho Varga]] ([[Michael Mando]]), in addition to becoming right-hand man for drug lord [[Gus Fring]] ([[Giancarlo Esposito]]) who runs a chain of fast food restaurants as a business front. Their operations are disrupted by members of the Salamanca crime family, including [[Lalo Salamanca]] ([[Tony Dalton]]). Odenkirk, Banks, and Esposito all reprise their roles from ''Breaking Bad''.\n\n''Better Call Saul'' has received critical acclaim, with particular praise for its acting, characters, and cinematography; many critics have called it a worthy successor to ''Breaking Bad'' and one of the best prequels ever made, with some deeming it superior to its predecessor.<ref name=\"sallgoodman\">{{cite web |last1=Heritage |first1=Stuart |title='S'all good, man': How Better Call Saul became superior to Breaking Bad |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/11/sall-good-man-how-better-call-saul-became-superior-to-breaking-bad |website=The Guardian |date=October 11, 2018 |accessdate=October 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Kelly |first=Stephen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jun/20/better-call-saul-breaking-bad-vince-gilligan |title=The perfect prequel: how Better Call Saul left Breaking Bad in its dust |work=The Guardian |date=June 20, 2017 |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Turner |first=Julia |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2016/04/18/better_call_saul_is_better_than_breaking_bad.html |title=Better Call Saul Is Better Than Breaking Bad |work=Slate |date=April 18, 2016 |accessdate=September 25, 2018}}</ref> It has garnered many nominations, including a [[Peabody Award]], 23 [[Primetime Emmy Awards]], eleven [[Writers Guild of America Awards]], five [[Critics' Choice Television Awards]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], and two [[Golden Globe Award]]s. The series premiere held the record for the highest-rated scripted series premiere in basic cable history at the time of its airing.\n\n== Premise ==\n''Better Call Saul'' follows the transformation of Jimmy McGill ([[Bob Odenkirk]]), a former con artist that is trying to become a respectable lawyer, into the personality of the flamboyant criminal lawyer [[Saul Goodman]] (a play on the phrase \"[it]'s all good, man!\"), over the six-year period prior to the events of ''Breaking Bad'' spanning from approximately 2002 to 2008.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/07/11/better-call-saul-photos |title='Better Call Saul': New photos, details from 'Breaking Bad' spin-off |first=James |last=Hibberd |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 11, 2014 |accessdate=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ew bbscenes\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/07/17/better-call-saul-breaking-bad-scene-season-4/ |title=Better Call Saul to show scenes set during Breaking Bad |first=Dan |last=Snierson |date=July 17, 2018 |accessdate=July 17, 2018 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Jimmy is inspired to turn his life around from his past \"Slippin' Jimmy\" con-man approach by his older brother [[Chuck McGill]] ([[Michael McKean]]), a senior partner alongside [[Howard Hamlin]] ([[Patrick Fabian]]) in the Albuquerque law firm Hamlin, Hamlin & McGill, as well as [[Kim Wexler]] ([[Rhea Seehorn]]), one of the firms legal associates who also becomes Jimmy's romantic interest.\n\nJimmy's initial pursuits during this period are focused on the public defense and earnest attempts to fight for proper justice while trying to get ahead, but soon his life and career starts to intersect with the illegal drug trade in the region, featuring characters and story arcs that continue into ''Breaking Bad''. This includes the uneasy truce between the Salamanca family that serves the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]] drug interest and later led by [[Lalo Salamanca]] ([[Tony Dalton]]) when their patriarch falls ill, and [[Gus Fring]] ([[Giancarlo Esposito]]), a restaurant entrepreneur that uses his stores as a front for the drug trade. Among those caught up in these events include [[Ignacio Varga|Ignacio \"Nacho\" Varga]] ([[Michael Mando]]), an enforcer for the Salamancas who only wants to protect his father from harm, and [[Mike Ehrmantraut]] ([[Jonathan Banks]]), a former police officer who becomes a [[fixer (person)|fixer]] for Gus.\n\nThe show also includes flash-forwards at the start of each season's premiere following the events of ''Breaking Bad'', where Saul has paid to take on a new identity as Gene Takovic, the manager of a [[Cinnabon]] store in [[Omaha, Nebraska]].\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Conception ===\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|align=right|total_width=300\n|image1=Vince_Gilligan_by_Gage_Skidmore_3.jpg\n|image2=Peter Gould by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|footer=''Better Call Saul'' was developed by [[Vince Gilligan]] (left) and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]].\n}}\n[[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]] began planning a [[television spinoff]] of ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' as early as 2009. While filming \"[[Full Measure (Breaking Bad)|Full Measure]]\", Gilligan asked [[Bob Odenkirk]], the actor of series character [[Saul Goodman]], what he thought of a spinoff of the show.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hiatt |first=Brian |date=March 16, 2015 |title=Bob Odenkirk on 'Saul' and 'Mr. Show'{{'}}s Non-Reunion |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/bob-odenkirk-on-better-call-saul-and-the-mr-show-non-reunion-96299/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref> In July 2012 Gilligan hinted at a possible Goodman spinoff,<ref name=\"comic-con interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/comic-con-qa-vince-gilligan-on-breaking-bad/ |title=Comic-Con Q&A: Vince Gilligan on 'Breaking Bad' |publisher=Deadline.com |date=July 15, 2012 |accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> stating that he liked \"the idea of a lawyer show in which the main lawyer will do anything it takes to stay out of a court of law\", including settling on the courthouse steps.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/09/breaking-bad-saul-goodman-spinoff-amc-series |title='Breaking Bad' Saul Goodman Spinoff A Go At AMC, Will Serve As Prequel To Original |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=September 11, 2013 |accessdate=September 13, 2013}}</ref> During his appearance on ''[[Talking Bad]],'' Odenkirk noted that Saul was one of the most popular characters on the show, speculating that the audience likes the character because he is the program's least hypocritical figure, and is good at his job.<ref>{{cite episode |series=Talking Bad |number=3 |network=AMC |airdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nGilligan noted that over the course of ''Breaking Bad'', there were a lot of \"what if\"s their team considered, such as if the show won a [[Primetime Emmy Award]], or if people would buy \"[[Los Pollos Hermanos]]\" T-shirts. The staff did not expect these events to come to fruition, but after they did, they started considering a spin-off featuring Saul as a thought experiment. Further, Saul's character on ''Breaking Bad'' became much more developed than the staff had originally planned, as he was originally slated to appear in only three episodes; with the growth of Saul's character, Gilligan saw ways to explore Saul's character further.<ref name=\"yahoo origin\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/blogs/tv-news/breaking-bad--spinoff-scoop-from-the-man-who-created-saul-goodman-014449665.html |title='Breaking Bad' Spinoff Scoop From the Man Who Created Saul Goodman |first=Kimberly |last=Potts |date=November 26, 2013 |accessdate=August 14, 2018 |work=[[Yahoo! News]]}}</ref>\n\n===Development===\nIn April 2013, ''Better Call Saul'' was confirmed to be in development by Gilligan and Gould; the latter wrote the [[Better Call Saul (Breaking Bad)|''Breaking Bad'' episode that introduced the character]].<ref name=\"deadline2\">{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/04/breaking-bad-spinoff-series-bob-odenkirk-saul-goodman-amc/ |title=AMC Eyes 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff Toplined By Bob Odenkirk |publisher=Deadline.com |date=April 9, 2013 |accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=IGN>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/09/11/breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-saul-confirmed |publisher=IGN |title=Breaking Bad Spinoff Series Better Call Saul Confirmed |first=Roth |last=Cornet |date=September 11, 2013 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> As of July 2013, the series had yet to be [[green-light|greenlighted]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Molloy |first=Tim |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tv/article/breaking-bad-creator-vince-gilligan-saul-goodman-spinoff-moving-full-speed-ahead-101091 |title=''Breaking Bad'' Creator Vince Gilligan: Saul Goodman Spinoff Moving 'Full Speed Ahead' |publisher=The Wrap |date=July 2, 2013 |accessdate=September 13, 2013}}</ref> [[Netflix]] was one of many interested distributors, but ultimately a deal was made between AMC and ''Breaking Bad'' production company [[Sony Pictures Television]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/breaking-bad-spinoff-how-amc-630464 |title=How AMC Almost Lost ''Breaking Bad'' Spinoff ''Better Call Saul'' to Netflix |last1=Guthrie |first1=Melissa |last2=Rose |first2=Lacey |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 18, 2013 |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> Gilligan and Gould serve as co-[[showrunner]]s and Gilligan directed the pilot.<ref name=numbers>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/06/19/amc-releases-first-photo-from-better-call-saul/275154/ |title='Better Call Saul' Renewed for Second Season by AMC; First Season Pushed Back to 2015 |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |work=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=June 19, 2014 |accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref> Former ''Breaking Bad'' writers [[Thomas Schnauz]] and [[Gennifer Hutchison]] joined the writing staff, with Schnauz serving as co-executive producer and Hutchison as supervising producer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/breaking-bad-writers-join-better-call-saul-staff-1200981189/ |title='Breaking Bad' Writers Join 'Better Call Saul' Staff |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |work=Variety |date=December 20, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> Also on the writing staff are [[Bradley Paul]], and [[Gordon Smith (screenwriter)|Gordon Smith]], who was a writer's assistant on ''Breaking Bad''.<ref name=numbers />\n\nAs Sony and AMC began to commit to a spinoff, Gilligan and Gould worked on what it would be about. They initially considered making it a half-hour show where Saul would see various clients \u2013 celebrities in guest roles \u2013 in his strip mall office, a format similar to ''[[Dr. Katz, Professional Therapist]]'', but they had no idea how to write for this type of format, and fell back onto planning for hour-long episodes.<ref name=\"rs creation\"/><ref name=\"deadline2\" /><ref name=\"deadline\" /> Since they had done this format with ''Breaking Bad'', which Gilligan said was \"25-percent humor, 75-percent drama\", the two considered reversing that for ''Better Call Saul''.<ref name=\"rs creation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-features/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-interview-704094/ |title=A Candid Conversation With Vince Gilligan on 'Better Call Saul' |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |authorlink=Alan Sepinwall |date=August 3, 2018 |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> While the intent was to add more humor, the show remained heavy with dramatic elements, with Odenkirk calling the first season \"85 percent drama, 15 percent comedy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/bob-odenkirk-better-call-saul-744069 |title=Bob Odenkirk on 'Better Call Saul': \"It's Total Drama\" |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Bryn Elise |last=Sandberg |date=October 27, 2014 |accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, while several of the characters are lawyers in the show, Gilligan and Gould did not want to write a legal show, but instead a crime show but one that would necessitate some legal elements. To help in these areas, the writers did speak to real lawyers and spent time observing cases at [[Los Angeles Superior Court]], observing that the bulk of the activity in these cases was downtime on waiting others to complete actions.<ref name=\"vox bcs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/2/3/7968975/better-call-saul-vince-gilligan |title=Better Call Saul's Vince Gilligan and Peter Gould on constructing the Breaking Bad spinoff |first=Emily |last=Todd vanDerWerff |date=February 3, 2015 |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]}}</ref>\n\nGilligan and Gould found that the character of Saul Goodman was not sufficient to carry the show by himself, with Gilligan calling the character of Saul \"great flavoring\" for a show but not the substance.<ref name=\"rs creation\"/> They came to realize that Saul, in the ''Breaking Bad'' timeframe, was a man that had come to accept himself, and recognized the potential to tell the story of how Saul got to be that person.<ref name=\"rs creation\"/> Gilligan and Gould had already committed to the ''Better Call Saul'' title, so that going this route, they believed they had to quickly get from Jimmy McGill to Saul Goodman or otherwise would disappoint their audience. However, as they wrote the show, they realized \"we don't want to get to Saul Goodman \u2026 and that's the tragedy\".<ref name=\"rs creation\"/> Gilligan and Gould had learned several lessons related to foreshadowing without writing the foresight for it from ''Breaking Bad'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uproxx.com/sepinwall/breaking-bad-10th-anniversary-vince-gilligan/ |title=Vince Gilligan On The Toughest Jams The 'Breaking Bad' Writers Put Walter White Into |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |date=January 17, 2018 |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |work=[[Uproxx]]}}</ref> and so with ''Better Call Saul'', gave themselves more flexibly in how the show's plot would develop over its run, and had no firm idea where it will end up outside the connection to ''Breaking Bad''.<ref name=\"rs creation\"/> For example, [[Rhea Seehorn]]'s performance as [[Kim Wexler]] during the first season significantly altered how the writers used her character in later seasons as well as slowed down the pacing of how fast they transitioned Jimmy into Saul, as they gave more focus to the Jimmy-Kim relationship. Gilligan compared this to the impact [[Aaron Paul]]'s outstanding acting had on ''Breaking Bad''{{'}}s ultimate pacing.<ref name=\"rs seehorn vip\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-features/better-call-saul-rhea-seehorn-interview-971200/ |title=How Rhea Seehorn Became the MVP of \u2018Better Call Saul\u2019 |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |authorlink=Alan Sepinwall |date=March 25, 2020 |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nIn writing for ''Better Call Saul'', Gilligan and Gould recognized they were including overlaps with ''Breaking Bad'', and had ideas of characters they would include, such as [[Gus Fring]], though on no set timetable within the show's development. Gilligan described the writing approach as if developing two separate shows, one that centers on Jimmy/Saul, Kim, Chuck, and Howard, and a second on the more familiar ''Breaking Bad'' characters like Mike and Gus with some overlap, so as if they were giving the audience two shows for one.<ref name=\"rs creation\"/> Where possible, they had written in minor ''Breaking Bad'' characters in smaller parts or as [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]] to fans, but for major ''Breaking Bad'' characters like Walter or Jesse, Gilligan preferred only to include them if their inclusion did not feel shoehorned in and feel less satisfactory to both the production team and to audiences.<ref name=\"rs creation\"/> Because of the closeness to the ''Breaking Bad'' storyline, one of the writers was tasked at the start of each season to rewatch all 62 episodes of the show and verify the scripts for the ''Better Call Saul'' season did not introduce any conflicts.<ref name=\"usatoday norris 2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/02/dean-norris-breaking-bad-dea-agent-better-call-saul/4895744002/ |title=Exclusive: Dean Norris on revisiting his 'Breaking Bad' character on 'Better Call Saul' |first=Bill |last=Keveney |date=March 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nNearing the start of filming of the pilot, Gilligan did become concerned which way audiences would take ''Better Call Saul'' as a spinoff, either favorably as ''[[Frasier]]'' or as a disappointment as with ''[[After MASH]]'', though felt his production team had done the best job they could for the show.<ref name=\"disappointment\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/03/breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-sail_n_5439788.html |title=Vince Gilligan Admits His 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff Might Be A Mistake |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=June 3, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014 |author=Toomer, Jessica}}</ref><ref name=\"moviefone\">{{cite web |url=http://news.moviefone.com/2014/06/03/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-mistake/ |title=Vince Gilligan Says 'Better Call Saul' Might Be a 'Mistake' |publisher=[[Moviefone]] |date=June 3, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014 |author=Roberts, Katie |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233510/http://news.moviefone.com/2014/06/03/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-mistake/ |archive-date=June 6, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\n[[Bob Odenkirk]] stars as lawyer Jimmy McGill (known as Saul Goodman in ''Breaking Bad''). In January 2014, it was announced that [[Jonathan Banks]] would reprise his ''Breaking Bad'' role as [[Mike Ehrmantraut]] and be a series regular.<ref name=\"Banks\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-enlists-jonathan-banks/ |title='Breaking Bad' Prequel 'Better Call Saul' Enlists Jonathan Banks |last=Kenneally |first=Tim |publisher=The Wrap |date=January 27, 2014 |accessdate=January 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nNew cast members include [[Michael McKean]] as McGill's elder brother Chuck. McKean previously guest-starred in an episode of Odenkirk's ''[[Mr. Show]]'' and Gilligan's ''[[The X-Files|X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Dreamland (The X-Files)|Dreamland]]\".<ref name=\"mckean\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/michael-mckean-better-call-saul-1201168991/ |title=Michael McKean Joins 'Breaking Bad' Prequel 'Better Call Saul' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=April 30, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |last=Friedlander |first=Whitney}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2015/04/06/michael_mckean_better_call_saul_is_about_the_american_escape_hatch_instead_of_the_american_dream/ |title=Michael McKean: \"Better Call Saul\" is about \"the American escape hatch instead of the American dream\" |work=Salon |first=Anna |last=Silman |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=April 3, 2016}}</ref> The cast also includes [[Patrick Fabian]] as [[Howard Hamlin]], [[Rhea Seehorn]] as Kimberly \"Kim\" Wexler, and [[Michael Mando]] as Ignacio \"Nacho\" Varga.<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/better-call-saul-cast-1201261529/ |title='Better Call Saul': Cast, Timeline Details and New Photos |last=Friedlander |first=Whitney |work=Variety |date=July 11, 2014 |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, [[Kerry Condon]] was cast<ref name=\"Condon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/movie-news/irish-actress-kerry-condon-scores-role-in-breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-saul-30629236.html |title=Irish actress Kerry Condon scores role in 'Breaking Bad' spin-off 'Better Call Saul' |work=The Independent |first=Aoife |last=Kelly |date=October 1, 2014 |accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> as Stacey Ehrmantraut, Mike's daughter-in-law. In November 2014, it was announced that [[Julie Ann Emery]] and [[Jeremy Shamos]] had been cast as Betsy and Craig Kettleman, described as \"the world's squarest outlaws.\"<ref name=\"Kettlemans\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/better-call-saul-adds-julie-ann-emery-and-jeremy-shamos-to-cast-1201354105/ |title='Better Call Saul' Adds Julie Ann Emery and Jeremy Shamos to Cast |last=Birnbaum |first=Debra |work=Variety |date=November 12, 2014 |accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nGoing into Season 3, it was announced that [[Giancarlo Esposito]] would return to play [[Gus Fring]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2017/01/14/giancarlo-esposito-cast-better-call-saul-season-3-gus-fring/ |title=Better Call Saul Season 3: Yep, Giancarlo Esposito Will Be Breaking Bad |last=Nemetz |first=Dave |work=TVLine |date=January 14, 2017 |accessdate=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Tony Dalton]] was announced as Lalo Salamanca for Season 4;<ref name=\"dalton lalo\"/> Lalo had been a character mentioned only by name, alongside Nacho, in the ''Breaking Bad'' episode \"[[Better Call Saul (Breaking Bad)|Better Call Saul]]\".<ref name=\"thr bb s4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/better-call-saul-bosses-breaking-bad-crossover-season-4-1121993 |title='Better Call Saul' and 'Breaking Bad' Overlap to Get \"Bigger and Bigger\" With Season 4 |first=Evan |last=Real |date=June 20, 2018 |accessdate=June 21, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Dean Norris]], another ''Breaking Bad'' alumnus, stated he could not be part of the earlier seasons, partly due to his involvement in the [[CBS]] series ''[[Under the Dome (TV series)|Under the Dome]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arts.nationalpost.com/2014/07/03/dean-norris-says-appearance-on-better-call-saul-unlikely-cbs-exec-les-moonves-wont-let-me-do-it/ |title=Dean Norris says appearance on Better Call Saul unlikely: CBS, exec Les Moonves 'won't let me do it' |work=[[The National Post]] |date=July 3, 2014 |accessdate=July 3, 2014 |author=Dekel, Jonathan |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140707075719/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2014/07/03/dean-norris-says-appearance-on-better-call-saul-unlikely-cbs-exec-les-moonves-wont-let-me-do-it/ |archivedate=July 7, 2014}}</ref> but was announced as a guest star reprising his role as [[Hank Schrader]] by Season 5.<ref name=\"BBCharacters\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/16/better-call-saul-season-5-robert-forster-dean-norris/ |title='Better Call Saul' season 5 to feature the late Robert Forster, Dean Norris |last=Snierson |first=Dan |date=January 16, 2020 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117041936/https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/16/better-call-saul-season-5-robert-forster-dean-norris/ |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther ''Breaking Bad'' actors have spoken of the potential of being on ''Better Call Saul''. Both [[Bryan Cranston]] and [[Aaron Paul]] said, as of Season 3, they are both open to reappearing on the show as [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] and [[Jesse Pinkman]], respectively, if asked, believing that Gilligan would have a sufficiently good reason to bring them in.<ref name=\"ew s4 cameos\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/06/29/bryan-cranston-aaron-paul-walt-jesse-better-call-saul/ |title=Breaking Bad creator 'desperately' wants Walt and Jesse in Better Call Saul |first=Dan |last=Snierson |date=June 29, 2018 |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Paul had previously mentioned the possibility of a cameo during Season 1 but this fell through.<ref name=\"pauldean\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/aaron-paul-wants-in-dean-norris-out-for-better-call-saul-the-breaking-bad-spinoff/2014/03/06/e3c521c0-a4b8-11e3-a5fa-55f0c77bf39c_story.html |title=Aaron Paul wants in, Dean Norris out for 'Better Call Saul,' the 'Breaking Bad' spinoff |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 9, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |last=Pearson |first=Ryan}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/13/aaron-paul-better-call-saul_n_5492079.html |title=Aaron Paul Offers Two Different 'Better Call Saul' Scenarios For Jesse Pinkman |work=The Huffington Post |date=June 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |author=Whitney, Erin}}</ref> [[Anna Gunn]] also mentioned a \"talk\" with Gilligan over possible guest appearances as Skyler White.<ref name=\"Anna\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/541399/anna-gunn-coming-to-breaking-bad-spinoff-star-reveals-there-s-been-talk-plus-why-we-re-dying-over-gracepoint |title=Anna Gunn Coming to ''Breaking Bad'' Spinoff? Star Reveals There's Been Talk\u2014Plus, Why We're Dying Over ''Gracepoint''! |publisher=[[E! Online]] |date=May 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014 |author=Dos Santos, Kristin}}</ref> Gilligan said that by Season 3 that show had been on long enough that any reuse of ''Breaking Bad'' characters would require more than \"just a cameo or an [[Alfred Hitchcock]] walkthrough\", and that their appearances would need to be essential for the story.<ref name=\"ew s4 cameos\"/>\n\n===Filming and production===\nLike its predecessor, ''Better Call Saul'' is set and filmed primarily in and around [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]].<ref name=\"filming\">{{cite web |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/06/02/breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-begins-filming-in-albuquerque-nm-today/ |title='Breaking Bad' prequel 'Better Call Saul' begins filming in Albuquerque, NM today! |publisher=On Location Vacations |date=June 2, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014 |author=Christine}}</ref> Notable locations include the Twisters restaurant used previously in ''Breaking Bad'' for Gus's Los Pollos Hermanos, a parking lot kiosk at the [[Albuquerque Convention Center]] for where Mike worked in the first few seasons, the Old Bernalillo County Courthouse as the local courthouse, and two nearby office buildings in the North Valley, include [[Northrop Grumman]]'s, that collectively are used for the HHM office spaces. Jimmy's back office is located in an actual nail salon, which the producers worked with the owners to accommodate, while the Salamanca's restaurant is also a real business in the South Valley that production modified a bit for the show, but otherwise remained an open business outside of filming. The scenes set in Omaha are actually filmed at [[Cottonwood Mall (Albuquerque, New Mexico)|Cottonwood Mall]] in Albuquerque; production worked with Cinnabon to bring in the period-specific equipment and service items for the segments, and the extras in the store during these scenes are Cinnabon employees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/better-call-saul-key-locations-albuquerque/ |title=Go behind the scenes of Better Call Saul's iconic Albuquerque locations |first=Dan |last=Snierson |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Additional filming took place at [[Albuquerque Studios]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1300873/better-call-saul-begins-filming-season-5-in-abq.html |title='Better Call Saul' begins filming season 5 in ABQ |website=Albuquerque Journal |first=Adrian |last=Gomez |date=April 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref> The New Mexico Film Office reported that the first four seasons of ''Better Call Saul'' had brought in over {{USD|120 million}} into the state, and has hired 1,600 crew for each season and a cumulative 11,300 extras.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1423575/abq-still-stars-in-amcs-better-call-saul.html |title=ABQ still stars in AMC's 'Better Call Saul' |first=Adrian |last=Gomez |date=February 22, 2020 |accessdate=February 24, 2020 |work=[[Albuquerque Journal]]}}</ref>\n\nFilming for the pilot started on June 2, 2014.<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/its-time-begin-overanalyzing-first-better-call-sau-205338 |title=It's time to begin overanalyzing the first ''Better Call Saul'' set photos |publisher=[[The Onion]] |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=June 3, 2014 |accessdate=June 4, 2014 |author=O'Neal, Sean}}</ref>\n\n''Better Call Saul'' also employs ''Breaking Bad''{{'}}s signature time jumps.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2013/12/31/breaking-bad-vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-community/2 |title='Breaking Bad' creator Vince Gilligan on the finale, 'Better Call Saul' and his acting debut on 'Community' |last=Snierson |first=Dan |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=December 31, 2013 |quote=We think, by and large, this show will be a prequel, but the wonderful thing about the fractured chronology we employed on ''Breaking Bad'' for many years is the audience will not be thrown by us jumping around in time. So it's possible that we may indeed do that, and we'll see the past and perhaps the future. |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref> Notably, each season pilot has started with a black and white flash-forward to a period in the years after the finale of ''Breaking Bad'' where Saul has been relocated to Omaha, Nebraska as \"Gene\", a manager of a Cinnabon store, remaining paranoid about anyone discovering his past identity as Saul.\n\n===Broadcast and marketing===\nThe first teaser trailer debuted on AMC on August 10, 2014, and confirmed its premiere date of February 2015.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/better-call-saul-first-teaser-trailer-shows-younger-saul-confirms-release-date-9660693.html |title=Better Call Saul: First teaser trailer shows younger Saul, confirms release date |work=The Independent |date=August 11, 2014 |accessdate=August 11, 2014 |author=Hooton, Christopher}}</ref> In November 2014, AMC announced the series would have a two-night premiere; the first episode aired on Sunday, February 8, 2015, at 10:00 pm (ET), and then moved into its regular time slot the following night, airing Mondays at 10:00 pm.<ref name=\"tvline\">{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2014/11/20/better-call-saul-premiere-date-amc/ |title=''Better Call Saul'' Gets Two-Night February Premiere on AMC |publisher=TVLine |date=November 20, 2014 |accessdate=November 20, 2014 |author=Roots, Kimberly}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, prior to the series' launch, AMC had renewed the series for a second season of 13 episodes to premiere in early 2016;<ref name=numbers /> however, it was later reduced to 10 episodes.<ref name=\"S02_Ep._Order_Reduced\">{{cite web |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Kevin |title='Better Call Saul' Season 2 Order Reduced from 13 Episodes |url=https://screencrush.com/better-call-saul-season-2-episodes-reduced/ |website=ScreenCrush |publisher=Townsquare Media, Inc. |date=November 17, 2015 |accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref> In May 2015, Gilligan confirmed that more of the prominent characters from ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' would be making guest appearances in season 2, but remained vague on which characters were likely to be seen.<ref name=\"christian today\">{{cite web |url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/better.call.saul.s2.more.breaking.bad.appearances.major.character.to.die/54130.htm |title='Better Call Saul' season 2 air date, spoilers, plot news: More 'Breaking Bad' appearances, major character to die next season? |date=May 20, 2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015 |author=Bernardino, Shiena}}</ref> The second season premiered on February 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/11/16/better-call-saul-returns-to-amc-in-february |title='Better Call Saul' returns to AMC in February |last=Porter |first=Rick |work=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=November 16, 2015 |accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, AMC announced that ''Better Call Saul'' was renewed for a 10-episode third season  which premiered April 10, 2017.<ref name=\"s3renew\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/15/better-call-saul-renewed-season-3 |title=''Better Call Saul'' renewed for season 3 by AMC |last=Snierson |first=Dan |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=March 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Schwindt |first1=Oriana |title=AMC Sets Premiere Dates for 'Better Call Saul,' 'Into the Badlands' |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/better-call-saul-s3-premiere-date-1201960755/ |accessdate=January 14, 2017 |work=Variety |date=January 14, 2017}}</ref> Following the season's end in June 2017, AMC renewed the series for a 10-episode fourth season which premiered on August 6, 2018.<ref name=\"s4renew\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/06/27/better-call-saul-renewed-season-4/ |title=Better Call Saul renewed for season 4 |work=Entertainment Weekly |last=Snierson |first=Dan |date=June 27, 2017 |accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/05/31/better-call-saul-season-4-premiere-date-first-look/ |title=Better Call Saul: Here's your season 4 first look, premiere date |work=Entertainment Weekly |last=Snierson |first=Dan |date=May 31, 2018 |accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe series was renewed for a fifth season on July 28, 2018, just prior to the airing of the fourth season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/better-call-saul-season-5-fear-the-walking-dead-season-5-mcmafia-season-2-renewed-amc-1202889278/ |title='Better Call Saul,' 'Fear the Walking Dead,' 'McMafia' Renewed at AMC |work=Variety |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=July 28, 2018 |accessdate=July 28, 2018}}</ref> The fifth season was not expected to air until 2020; according to AMC's Sarah Barnett, the delay was \"driven by talent needs\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/04/killing-eve-amc-networks-bbc-america-strategy.html |title=Why AMC Networks Is Betting So Heavily on Killing Eve |first=Josef |last=Adalian |date=April 5, 2019 |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |work=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]}}</ref> Filming for the fifth season started in April 2019, and finished in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1300873/better-call-saul-begins-filming-season-5-in-abq.html |title='Better Call Saul' begins filming season 5 in ABQ |first=Adrian |last=Gomez |date=April 8, 2019 |accessdate=April 8, 2019 |work=[[The Albuquerque Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvinsider.com/811132/better-call-saul-season-5-wrap-ending/ |title='Better Call Saul' Wraps Season 5 \u2013 Could It Be The Show's Last? |first=Meaghan |last=Darwish |date=September 9, 2019 |accessdate=September 9, 2019 |work=TV Insider}}</ref> AMC later affirmed the ten-episode fifth season will start airing with a special Sunday broadcast on February 23, 2020, with following episodes to air on Mondays.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/better-clal-saul-season-five-premiere-date-teaser-915197/ |title='Better Call Saul' Cooks Up Clever Cinnabon Spot for Season Five Premiere |first=Jon |last=Blistein |date=November 20, 2019 |accessdate=November 20, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, AMC renewed the series for a sixth season that is scheduled to air in 2021,<ref name=\"FinalSeason\"/> though will depend on whether they will be able to film in the last part of 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-features/better-call-saul-season-5-finale-creators-interview-984340/| title= 5 Burning Questions About the \u2018Better Call Saul\u2019 Season 5 Finale \u2014 Answered| first = Alan | last = Sepinwall | author-link = Alan Sepinwall | date = April 20, 2020 | accessdate = April 21, 2020 | work = [[Rolling Stone]] }}</ref> Gould confirmed it will be the show's final season, and will consist of 13 episodes rather than the usual 10. This will bring the show's final episode count to 63, one more than its predecessor ''Breaking Bad''. Gould stated: \"From the beginning when we started this, I think all our hopes and dreams were to be able to tell the whole story ... and make it to be a complete story from beginning to end. We're going to try like hell to stick the landing of these 63 episodes\".<ref name=\"FinalSeason\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/better-call-saul-ending-season-6-amc-1267357 |title='Better Call Saul' Ending With Season 6 on AMC |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Rick |last=Porter |date=January 16, 2020 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 125\n\n| image1    = Bob Odenkirk by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption1  = [[Bob Odenkirk]] ([[Saul Goodman|Jimmy McGill / Saul Goodman]])\n\n| image2    = Jonathan Banks 2012 2.jpg\n| caption2  = [[Jonathan Banks]] ([[Mike Ehrmantraut]])\n\n| image3    = Rhea Seehorn by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption3  = [[Rhea Seehorn]] ([[Kim Wexler]])\n\n| image4    = Patrick Fabian by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption4  = [[Patrick Fabian]] ([[Howard Hamlin]])\n\n| image5    = Michael Mando by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption5  = [[Michael Mando]] ([[Nacho Varga]])\n\n| image6    = MichaelMcKeanApr09cropped.jpg\n| caption6  = [[Michael McKean]] ([[Chuck McGill]])\n\n| image7    = Giancarlo Esposito by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption7  = [[Giancarlo Esposito]] ([[Gus Fring]])\n\n| image8     = Tony Dalton (cropped).jpg\n| caption8   = [[Tony Dalton]] ([[Lalo Salamanca]])\n}}\n\n=== Main cast ===\n{{see also|List of Breaking Bad and Better Call Saul characters}}\n* [[Bob Odenkirk]] as [[Saul Goodman|Jimmy McGill / Saul Goodman / Gene Takavic]], a lawyer and a former [[scam artist]], who becomes involved with the criminal world.\n* [[Jonathan Banks]] as [[Mike Ehrmantraut]], a former [[Philadelphia Police Department|Philadelphia police officer]] working as a parking lot attendant at the Albuquerque court house, and later a private investigator, bodyguard and \"[[Fixer (person)|cleaner]]\".\n* [[Rhea Seehorn]] as [[Kim Wexler]], a lawyer who Jimmy met as she worked her way through the ranks at the Hamlin, Hamlin & McGill (HHM) law firm, and is Jimmy's girlfriend and confidante.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/better-call-saul-premiere-jimmy-love-interest-kim-wexler-1201425526/ |title='Better Call Saul' Premiere: Meet Jimmy McGill's Love Interest |first=Debra |last=Birnbaum |date=February 6, 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Corporation]] |accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"etonline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/161233_better_call_saul_rhea_seehron_on_kim_and_jimmy_complicated_past_i_think_she_loves_him/ |title='Better Call Saul's Rhea Seehorn on Kim and Jimmy's Complicated Past: 'She Loves Him' |first=Leanne |last=Aguilera |date=March 16, 2015 |work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |publisher=[[CBS Corporation]] |accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Patrick Fabian]] as [[Howard Hamlin]], the managing partner at Hamlin, Hamlin & McGill, first appearing as Jimmy's nemesis, until it becomes clear that he was acting under Chuck McGill's orders.\n* [[Michael Mando]] as [[Nacho Varga]], who works in his father's upholstery shop and is also an intelligent, ambitious member of Hector Salamanca's gang.\n* [[Michael McKean]] as [[Chuck McGill]], Jimmy's elder brother and a founding partner of HHM who is confined to his home by [[electromagnetic hypersensitivity]] and expresses disdain for his brother's legal abilities. (seasons 1\u20133, recurring season 4)\n* [[Giancarlo Esposito]] as [[Gus Fring]], the owner of the [[fast food]] restaurant chain Los Pollos Hermanos that he uses as a front for distributing [[cocaine]] for the Mexican cartel in uneasy cooperation with the Salamanca family, with larger desires to switch the drug trade to the more profitable [[methamphetamine]] that would eliminate his dependence to the cartel. (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* [[Tony Dalton]] as [[Lalo Salamanca]], nephew of Hector and cousin of Tuco, Leonel, and Marco, who helps run the family drug business after Hector's stroke. (season 5\u2013present, recurring season 4)<ref name=\"dalton lalo\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/better-call-saul-tony-dalton-series-regular-season-5-1202591334/ |title='Better Call Saul' Adds Tony Dalton As Series Regular For Season 5 |first=Dino-Ray |last=Ramos |date=April 8, 2019 |work=Deadline |accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Recurring cast ===\n====Introduced in season 1====\n* [[Kerry Condon]] as Stacey Ehrmantraut, Mike's widowed daughter-in-law and the mother of Kaylee Ehrmantraut.\n* Faith Healey (season 1), Abigail Zoe Lewis (seasons 2\u20134) and Juliet Donenfeld (season 5-present) as Kaylee Ehrmantraut, Mike's granddaughter.\n* Eileen Fogarty as Mrs. Nguyen, owner of a nail salon which houses Jimmy's law office in its utility room.\n* Peter Diseth as Bill Oakley, a deputy district attorney.\n* [[Joe DeRosa (comedian)|Joe DeRosa]] as Dr. Caldera, a veterinarian with ties to the criminal underworld.\n* [[Dennis Boutsikaris]] as Rich Schweikart, a partner at Schweikart & Cokely.\n* [[Mark Proksch]] as Daniel \"Pryce\" Wormald, a drug company employee who begins supplying Nacho and hires Mike as security.\n* Brandon K. Hampton as Ernesto, Chuck's assistant who works at HHM.\n* [[Josh Fadem]] as Camera Guy, or Joey Dixon, one of the three University of New Mexico (UNM) film students who help Jimmy film various projects.\n* Julian Bonfiglio as Sound Guy, one of the three UNM film students Jimmy hires for various film projects.\n* [[Jeremy Shamos]] and [[Julie Ann Emery]] as Craig and Betsy Kettleman, a county treasurer and his wife, accused of embezzlement.\n* Steven Levine and Daniel Spenser Levine as Lars and Cal Lindholm, [[twin]] skateboarders and small-time scam artists.\n* [[M\u00edriam Col\u00f3n]] as Abuelita Salamanca, Tuco's grandmother and Hector's mother.\n* [[Barry Shabaka Henley]] as Detective Sanders, a [[Philadelphia]] cop who was formerly partnered with Mike on the force.\n* [[Mel Rodriguez]] as Marco Pasternak, Jimmy's best friend and partner-in-crime in [[Cicero, Illinois]].\n* [[Clea DuVall]] as Dr. Cruz, a doctor who treats Chuck and suspects his electromagnetic hypersensitivity condition is [[psychosomatic]].\n* Jean Effron as Irene Landry, an elderly client of Jimmy McGill overcharged by the Sandpiper Crossing elder care home.\n* [[Steven Ogg]] as Sobchak, a petty crook for hire.\n\n====Introduced in season 2====\n* [[Ed Begley Jr.]] as Clifford Main, managing partner at Davis & Main.\n* Omar Maskati as Omar, Jimmy's assistant at Davis & Main.\n* Jessie Ennis as Erin Brill, a lawyer at Davis & Main who is ordered to shadow Jimmy.\n* Juan Carlos Cantu as Manuel Varga, Nacho's father who owns an upholstery shop.\n* Vincent Fuentes as Arturo Colon, a criminal associate of Hector Salamanca (seasons 2\u20134).\n* [[Rex Linn]] as Kevin Wachtell, chairman of Mesa Verde Bank and Trust and a client of HHM and Kim.\n* [[Cara Pifko]] as Paige Novick, senior legal counsel for Mesa Verde Bank and Trust and a friend of Kim.\n* [[Ann Cusack]] as Rebecca Bois, Chuck's ex-wife.\n* Manuel Uriza as Ximenez Lecerda, an associate of Hector Salamanca.\n* Hayley Holmes as Drama Girl, one of the three UNM film students Jimmy hires for various projects.\n\n====Introduced in season 3====\n* [[Bonnie Bartlett]] as Helen, Irene's friend and member of the affected class in the Sandpiper lawsuit.\n* [[Kimberly Hebert Gregory]] as Assistant District Attorney Kyra Hay.\n* [[Tamara Tunie]] as Anita, a member of Mike and Stacey's support group.\n\n====Introduced in season 4====\n* [[Rainer Bock]] as Werner Ziegler, an engineer hired by Gus to plan and oversee construction of his meth \"superlab\".\n* Ben Bela B\u00f6hm as Kai, a rebellious member of the crew Werner Ziegler assembles for the construction of Gus's meth \"superlab\".\n* [[Stefan Kapi\u010di\u0107]] as Casper, a member of Werner Ziegler's team.\n* [[Poorna Jagannathan]] as Maureen Bruckner, a specialist from [[Johns Hopkins Hospital|Johns Hopkins]] who flew to Albuquerque to treat Hector after Gus arranged for a \"generous grant.\"\n\n====Introduced in season 5====\n* Sasha Feldman and Morgan Krantz as Sticky and Ron, two petty crooks that are among \"Saul Goodman\"{{'s}} first clients.\n* [[Barry Corbin]] as Everett Acker, an old man living on leased property belonging to Mesa Verde who becomes a legal matter for Kim to evict to make way for the bank's new [[call center]].\n\n====''Breaking Bad'' characters====\n* [[Raymond Cruz]] as [[Tuco Salamanca]], a ruthless, psychopathic drug distributor in the South Valley. (seasons 1\u20132)\n* Cesar Garc\u00eda as No-Doze, Tuco's henchman. (season 1)\n* Jes\u00fas Pay\u00e1n Jr. as Gonzo, Tuco's henchman. (season 1)\n* T.C. Warner as Nurse (season 1)\n* [[Kyle Bornheimer]] as [[Cancer Man (Breaking Bad)#Plot|Ken]], an arrogant, self-absorbed stockbroker (season 2)\n* Stoney Westmoreland as Officer Saxton, an [[Albuquerque Police Department]] officer (season 2)\n* [[Jim Beaver]] as [[List of Breaking Bad characters#Lawson|Lawson]], a black market weapons dealer in Albuquerque (season 2)\n* Maximino Arciniega as [[List of Breaking Bad characters#Krazy-8 Molina|Domingo \"Krazy-8\" Molina]], one of Tuco's distributors (seasons 2\u2013present)\n* [[Mark Margolis]] as [[Hector Salamanca]], Tuco's uncle and high-ranking member of the cartel (seasons 2\u2013present)\n* Debrianna Mansini as Fran, a waitress at Loyola's Diner (seasons 2, 4)\n* [[Daniel and Luis Moncada]] as [[List of Breaking Bad characters#Leonel and Marco Salamanca|Leonel and Marco Salamanca]], Tuco's cousins and Hector's nephews who are hitmen for the cartel (seasons 2, 4\u2013present)\n* Jennifer Hasty as Stephanie Doswell, a real estate agent (season 2)\n* [[Tina Parker]] as Francesca Liddy, Jimmy's receptionist (seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Jeremiah Bitsui]] as Victor, Gus's henchman (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* Ray Campbell as Tyrus Kitt, a henchman on Gus Fring's payroll (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* [[JB Blanc]] as Dr. Barry Goodman, a doctor on Gus Fring's payroll (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* [[Steven Bauer]] as Don Eladio Vuente, the head of the Juarez drug cartel (seasons 3 and 5)\n* Javier Grajeda as Juan Bolsa, a high-level member of the Ju\u00e1rez drug cartel (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* [[Lavell Crawford]] as Huell Babineaux, a professional pickpocket hired by Jimmy (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* [[Laura Fraser]] as [[Lydia Rodarte-Quayle]], a Madrigal Electromotive executive and associate of Gus Fring (seasons 3\u2013present)\n* Eric Steining as Nick, a member of Gus's security team, later managed by Mike. (seasons 4\u2013present)\n* Franc Ross as Ira, a burglar Jimmy hires; in ''Breaking Bad'', he is the owner of Vamonos Pest who appears in \"[[Hazard Pay]]\". (season 4)\n* [[David Costabile]] as [[Gale Boetticher]], a chemist who is consulted by Gus (season 4)\n* [[Robert Forster]] as [[List of Breaking Bad and Better Call Saul characters#Ed Galbraith|Ed Galbraith]], a vacuum cleaner store owner who relocates people running from the law and gives them new identities. (season 5)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/16/better-call-saul-season-5-robert-forster-dean-norris/ |title='Better Call Saul' season 5 to feature the late Robert Forster, Dean Norris |website=Entertainment Weekly |first=Dan |last=Snierson |date=January 16, 2020 |access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Dean Norris]] as [[Hank Schrader]], a DEA agent and [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]]'s brother-in-law (season 5)<ref name=\"FinalSeason\"/>\n* [[Steven Michael Quezada]] as [[Steven Gomez|Steven \"Gomey\" Gomez]], Hank's DEA partner and best friend (season 5)<ref name=\"FinalSeason\"/>\n* Nigel Gibbs as Tim Roberts, a detective with the Albuquerque Police Department (season 5)\n* [[Norbert Weisser]] as Peter Schuler, a Madrigal Electromotive executive and associate of Gus Fring (season 5)\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{see also|List of Better Call Saul episodes}}\n{{:List of Better Call Saul episodes}}\n\n=== Season 1 (2015) ===\n{{see also|Better Call Saul (season 1)}}\nTired of public defender work, Jimmy works to represent the Kettlemans, who are accused of embezzlement. Jimmy cares for his brother Chuck, who is housebound without electricity because he believes he has electromagnetic hypersensitivity. While pursuing an elder law career, Jimmy discovers clients being defrauded by the Sandpiper retirement home and begins a class action lawsuit with Chuck. When the case grows, Chuck suggests giving it to HHM, but secretly arranges with Howard to cut Jimmy out. The case continues growing and HHM brings on Davis & Main. Unhappy at Howard's treatment of him, Kim recommends Jimmy to D&M.\n\n=== Season 2 (2016) ===\n{{see also|Better Call Saul (season 2)}}\nJimmy works at D&M but quits after being reprimanded for his client outreach methods. Kim is demoted because of Jimmy's actions. To reclaim her status, she secures Mesa Verde Bank as a client for HHM but Howard denies her credit. Kim quits at HHM, and she and Jimmy begin separate private practices in a shared office. Jimmy secretly causes Chuck to make an error that delays a new branch construction, so Mesa Verde drops HHM to hire Kim. Nacho hires Mike to remove Tuco from the Salamanca organization. Mike goads Tuco into fighting and Tuco is imprisoned. Hector is suspicious so Mike prepares to assassinate him but is interrupted.\n\n=== Season 3 (2017) ===\n{{see also|Better Call Saul (season 3)}}\nChuck discovers Jimmy's fraud and tricks him into confessing, leading to suspension of Jimmy's law license. Chuck's ouster at HHM leads to his suicide.  Gus stops Mike from killing Hector. Mike attacks Hector's trucks and steals $250,000 from one. Mike asks for help laundering the money. Gus arranges for Mike's hire as a contracted security expert at Madrigal and payment of monthly consulting fees. Hector plans to take over Manuel's business so Nacho attempts to kill Hector by changing his angina medication for a placebo. Hector suffers a stroke and Gus\u2019 first aid saves him, though he remains comatose.\n\n=== Season 4 (2018) ===\n{{see also|Better Call Saul (season 4)}}\nJimmy regains his outgoing demeanor after Howard shoulders blame for Chuck's death. Jimmy manages a cell phone store but makes more reselling prepaid phones. His law license reinstatement request is denied over lack of remorse for Chuck. After faking mourning, he successfully appeals, but reveals he is going to practice as Saul Goodman. Gus learns Nacho attempted to kill Hector and blackmails him into undermining the Salamancas. Mike escorts engineers who evaluate the laundry's potential as a meth lab and Gus hires Werner to oversee construction. Hector recovers mentally and can move his right index finger. Lalo Salamanca arrives to run Hector's business.\n\n===Season 5 (2020)===\n{{see also|Better Call Saul (season 5)}}\nJimmy's new business as Saul Goodman draws him into the drug trade within Alburquerque. Kim herself balances her Mesa Verde and ''pro bono'' work with her own feelings for Jimmy, and finds herself toying with the same conman-style tactics Jimmy employs within her casework. Lalo's presence forces Gus to halt the superlab construction, and both Nacho and Mike become pawns in the ongoing feud between the Salamancas and Gus.\n\n==''Talking Saul''==\n''Talking Saul'' is a [[live television|live]] [[aftershow]] hosted by [[Chris Hardwick]], which features guests discussing episodes of ''Better Call Saul''. The show uses the same format as ''[[Talking Dead]],'' ''[[Talking Bad]],'' and other similar aftershows also hosted by Hardwick. AMC announced that ''Talking Saul'' would air after the second season ''Better Call Saul'' premiere on February 15, 2016, and again after the second-season finale on April 18, 2016.<ref name=\"talking saul\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/talking-saul-after-show-better-call-saul-premiere-finale-amc-1201701500/ |title='Talking Saul' To Follow 'Better Call Saul's Premiere And Season Finale On AMC |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=February 12, 2016 |accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref> It returned following the season 3 premiere and finale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amc.com/shows/talking-saul/talk/2017/03/talking-saul-returns-with-special-guests-vince-gilligan-peter-gould-and-more |title=Talking Saul Returns With Special Guests Vince Gilligan, Peter Gould and More |publisher=AMC |first=Marissa |last=Shapiro |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Season 1 (2016)<!--This refers to season 1 of Talking Saul, NOT Better Call Saul-->===\nThese episodes discuss [[Better Call Saul (season 2)|season two]] of ''Better Call Saul''.\n\n{{Episode table |background=#615743 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=19 |aux1=48 |airdate=13 |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |titleT=Episode discussed |aux1T=Guests |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = [[Switch (Better Call Saul)|Switch]]\n |Aux1            = [[Vince Gilligan]], [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]], [[Bob Odenkirk]] and [[Rhea Seehorn]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|2|15}}\n |Viewers         = 0.744<ref name=\"Welch\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2016/02/17/monday-cable-ratings-wwe-raw-stays-steady-better-call-saul-premieres-low/ |title=Monday cable ratings: 'WWE Raw' stays steady, 'Better Call Saul' premieres low |work=TV by the Numbers |last=Welch |first=Alex |date=February 17, 2016 |accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    =\n |LineColor       = 615743\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = [[Klick (Better Call Saul)|Klick]]\n |Aux1            = [[Jonathan Banks]], Vince Gilligan and Peter Gould\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|4|18}}\n |Viewers         = 0.641<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-4-18-2016.html |title=SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 4.18.2016 |work=Showbuzz Daily |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=April 19, 2016 |accessdate=April 19, 2016}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    =\n |LineColor       = 615743\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 2 (2017)<!--This refers to season 2 of Talking Saul, NOT Better Call Saul-->===\nThese episodes discuss [[Better Call Saul (season 3)|season three]] of ''Better Call Saul''.\n\n{{Episode table |background=#3B3B48 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=19 |aux1=48 |airdate=13 |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |titleT=Episode discussed |aux1T=Guests |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n |Title           = [[Mabel (Better Call Saul)|Mabel]]\n |Aux1            = Vince Gilligan, Peter Gould, Jonathan Banks and Rhea Seehorn\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|4|10}}\n |Viewers         = 0.545<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-4-10-2017.html |title=SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 4.10.2017 |work=Showbuzz Daily |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    =\n |LineColor       = 3B3B48\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n |Title           = [[Lantern (Better Call Saul)|Lantern]]\n |Aux1            = Peter Gould, [[Patrick Fabian]] and [[Michael Mando]]; [[Michael McKean]] via satellite\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2017|6|19}}\n |Viewers         = 0.589<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-6-19-2017.html |title=SHOWBUZZDAILY's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 5.19.2017 |work=Showbuzz Daily |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=June 20, 2017 |accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary    =\n |LineColor       = 3B3B48\n}}\n}}\n\n== Broadcast ==\n''Better Call Saul'' airs on cable network [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]. The series premiere drew in 4.4 million and 4 million in the 18\u201349 and 25\u201354 demographics, respectively, and received an overall viewership of 6.9 million.<ref name=\"premiere ratings\">{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/09/the-walking-dead-returns-to-15-6-million-viewers-better-call-saul-is-biggest-series-premiere-in-cable-history/361195/ |title='The Walking Dead' Returns to 15.6 Million Viewers + 'Better Call Saul' is Biggest Series Premiere in Cable History |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Amanda |last=Kondolojy |date=February 9, 2015 |accessdate=February 9, 2015}}</ref> This was the record for the highest-rated scripted series premiere in basic cable history, until it was surpassed later the same year by another AMC series, ''[[Fear the Walking Dead]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title='Fear The Walking Dead' Debut Ratings Draw 10.1M Viewers, Shatters Cable Records |url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/fear-the-walking-dead-ratings-the-walking-dead-companion-series-amc-1201504381/ |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Dominic |last=Patten |date=August 24, 2015 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, [[Netflix]] announced that the entire first season would be available for streaming in the U.S. after the airing of the first-season finale, and in Latin America and Europe each episode would be available a few days after the episode airs in the U.S.<ref name=\"netflix\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2013/digital/news/netflix-to-stream-better-call-saul-after-amc-airs-breaking-bad-spinoff-in-2014-1200962667/ |title=Netflix to Stream 'Better Call Saul' After AMC Airs 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff in 2014 |work=Variety |first=Todd |last=Spangler |date=December 16, 2013 |accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref> However, the first season was not released on Netflix in the U.S. until February 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/02/7-new-netflix-shows-to-binge-watch-in-february-2016-and-the-best-episodes-of-each-28412/ |title=7 New Netflix Shows to Binge Watch in February 2016 (And the Best Episodes of Each) |work=IndieWire |first=Ben |last=Travers |date=February 1, 2016 |accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/01/whats-new-on-netflix-february-2016.html |title=What's New on Netflix: February 2016 |work=Vulture |first=Jackson |last=McHenry |date=January 29, 2016 |accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref> Internationally, episodes of the second season became available the day after they aired in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/02/netflix-better-call-saul-streaming-next-day |title=Netflix to Stream Episodes of Better Call Saul Internationally the Day After They Air [Updated] |work=Vanity Fair |first=Joanna |last=Robinson |date=February 1, 2016 |accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nNetflix is the exclusive video-on-demand provider for the series and makes the content available in all its territories, except for [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"netflix\" /> In Australia, ''Better Call Saul'' premiered on the [[streaming media|streaming service]] [[Stan (streaming company)|Stan]]<ref name=\"Stanlaunchshows\">{{cite web |title=Stan launches on Australia Day |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/01/stan-launches-on-australia-day.html |publisher=TV Tonight |date=January 23, 2015 |accessdate=January 23, 2015}}</ref> on February 9, 2015, acting as the service's flagship program.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mumbrella.com.au/stan-launch-australia-day-272407 |title=Video streaming service Stan to launch on Australia Day |publisher=mUmBRELLA |date=January 22, 2015 |accessdate=January 24, 2015}}</ref> In New Zealand, the show is exclusive to the New Zealand-based subscription video-on-demand service, [[Lightbox (New Zealand)|Lightbox]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Breaking Bad spin-off Better Call Saul coming to Lightbox |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11364678 |accessdate=June 21, 2015 |work=The New Zealand Herald |date=November 27, 2014}}</ref> The episodes were available for viewing within three days of broadcast in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |title=The court is in session: Better Call Saul on Lightbox |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1501/S00369/the-court-is-in-session-better-call-saul-on-lightbox.htm |accessdate=June 21, 2015 |publisher=Scoop |date=January 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom and Ireland, the series was acquired by Netflix on December 16, 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/12/netflix-uk-ireland-inks-spt-deal-exclusive-rights-breaking-bad-spin-better-call-saul/ |title=Netflix UK & Ireland Inks SPT Deal For Exclusive Rights To 'Breaking Bad' Spin-Off 'Better Call Saul' |last=Munn |first=Patrick |publisher=TV Wise |date=December 16, 2013 |accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref> and the first episode premiered on February 9, 2015, with the second episode released the following day. Every subsequent episode was released each week thereafter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2015/01/netflix-uk-unveils-trailer-breaking-bad-spin-off-better-call-saul/ |title=Netflix UK Unveils Trailer For 'Breaking Bad' Spin-Off 'Better Call Saul' |date=January 27, 2015 |last=Munn |first=Patrick |publisher=TV Wise |accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref> In India, the series is broadcast on [[Colors Infinity]] within 24 hours of the U.S. broadcast.<ref>{{cite web |first=Shilpa |last=Bansal |title='Better Call Saul' Season 2 India Premiere: Where to watch Episode 1 'Switch' on TV tonight [Spoilers] |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/better-call-saul-season-2-india-premiere-where-watch-episode-1-switch-tv-tonight-spoilers-667174 |publisher=International Business Times |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |date=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''Better Call Saul'' has received critical acclaim.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin-left:1em;\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#133E51;\"|\n| [[Better Call Saul (season 1)|1]]\n| 97% (68 reviews)<ref name=\"rt-s1\" />\n| 78 (43 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#CFB7A0;\"|\n|  [[Better Call Saul (season 2)|2]]\n| 97% (31 reviews)<ref name=\"rt-s2\" />\n| 85 (18 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#4F4F5E;\"|\n| [[Better Call Saul (season 3)|3]]\n| 97% (39 reviews)<ref name=\"rt-s3\" />\n| 87 (18 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#111111;\"|\n| [[Better Call Saul (season 4)|4]]\n| 99% (36 reviews)<ref name=\"rt-s4\" />\n| 87 (16 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#6d4955;\"|\n| [[Better Call Saul (season 5)|5]]\n| 99% (33 reviews)<ref name=\"rt-s5\" />\n| 92 (16 reviews)\n|}\n\n====Season 1====\n{{see also|Better Call Saul (season 1)#Reception}}\nThe first season of ''Better Call Saul'' received critical acclaim, particularly for its acting, writing, and directing with many critics calling it a worthy successor to ''Breaking Bad''. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season has a rating of 97%, based on 68 reviews, with an average rating of 8.03/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Better Call Saul'' is a quirky, dark character study that manages to stand on its own without being overshadowed by the series that spawned it.\"<ref name=\"rt-s1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/better-call-saul/s01/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season 1 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref> On the review aggregator website [[Metacritic]], the first season has a score of 78 out of 100, based on 43 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/better-call-saul/season-1 |title=Better Call Saul : Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=February 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Season 2====\n{{main|Better Call Saul (season 2)#Reception}}\nThe second season, much like the previous, received critical acclaim. On Rotten Tomatoes, the second season has a score of 97%, based on 31 reviews, with an average rating of 8.7/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Better Call Saul'' continues to tighten its hold on viewers with a batch of episodes that inject a surge of dramatic energy while showcasing the charms of its talented lead.\"<ref name=\"rt-s2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/better-call-saul/s02/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season 2 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref> On Metacritic, the second season has a score of 85 out of 100, based on 18 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/better-call-saul/season-2 |title=Better Call Saul : Season 2 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Season 3====\n{{main|Better Call Saul (season 3)#Reception}}\nThe third season, much like the previous two, received critical acclaim, particularly for the character development of Jimmy McGill. On Rotten Tomatoes, the third season has an approval rating of 97% based on 39 reviews, with an average rating of 8.78/10. The site's critical consensus is, \"''Better Call Saul'' shows no signs of slipping in season 3, as the introduction of more familiar faces causes the inevitable transformation of its lead to pick up exciting speed.\"<ref name=\"rt-s3\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/better-call-saul/s03/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season 3 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the season has a score of 87 out of 100, based on 18 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/better-call-saul/season-3 |title=Better Call Saul : Season 3 |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=April 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Season 4====\n{{main|Better Call Saul (season 4)#Reception}}\nThe fourth season also received critical acclaim. On Rotten Tomatoes, the season has a 99% approval rating with an average score of 8.93 out of 10 based on 36 reviews. The site's critical consensus states, \"Well-crafted and compelling as ever, ''Better Call Saul'' deftly balances the show it was and the one it will inevitably become.\"<ref name=\"rt-s4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/better_call_saul/s04/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season 4 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> On Metacritic, the season has a score of 87 out of 100, based on 16 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/better-call-saul/season-4 |title=Better Call Saul : Season 4 |website=Metacritic |accessdate=August 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Season 5====\n{{main|Better Call Saul (season 5)#Reception}}\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the season has an approval rating of 99% based on 33 reviews, with an average rating of 8.82/10. The website's critical consensus is, \"Grounded by Bob Odenkirk's endlessly nuanced, lived-in performance, ''Better Call Saul''{{'}}s fifth season is a darkly funny, vividly realized master class in tragedy.\"<ref name=\"rt-s5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/better-call-saul/s05/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season 5 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the season has a score of 92 out of 100 based on 16 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/better-call-saul/season-5 |title=Better Call Saul: Season 5 |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipients\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=12| 2015\n|[[American Film Institute Awards 2015|2015 American Film Institute Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/about/releases/2015/AFI_Awards_2015_Announced.aspx |title=AFI AWARDS 2015 OFFICIAL SELECTIONS |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |date=December 16, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n|Television Programs of the Year\n|''Better Call Saul''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[5th Critics' Choice Television Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2015/05/31/critics-choice-television-awards-winners-2015-full-list/ |title=Critics' Choice Television Awards: HBO, ''Better Call Saul'', Taraji P. Henson and Amy Schumer Among Big Winners |publisher=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=May 31, 2015 |accessdate=June 1, 2015}}</ref>\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Drama Series|Best Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Bob Odenkirk]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Jonathan Banks]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[31st TCA Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2015/08/08/tca-award-winners-empire-program-of-year-2015/ |title=TCA Awards 2015: ''Empire'', Jon Hamm, Amy Schumer, ''Americans'', ''Fosters'' and John Oliver Among Winners |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=August 8, 2015 |accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| [[TCA Award for Outstanding New Program|Outstanding New Program]]\n| ''Better Call Saul''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| [[TCA Award for Individual Achievement in Drama|Individual Achievement in Drama]]\n| Bob Odenkirk\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[67th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]<ref name=\"emmys\" />\n| rowspan=2|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Single-Camera Picture Editing for a Drama Series]]\n| Kelley Dixon (\"[[Five-O (Better Call Saul)|Five-O]]\")\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Kelley Dixon and [[Chris McCaleb]] (\"[[Marco (Better Call Saul)|Marco]]\")\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Sound Mixing for a Comedy or Drama Series (One-Hour)|Outstanding Sound Mixing for a Comedy or Drama Series]]\n| Phillip W. Palmer, Larry Benjamin, Kevin Valentine (\"Marco\")\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[67th Primetime Emmy Awards]]<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/07/emmy-award-nominations-2015-full-list-1201476759/ |title=Emmy Nominations 2015 \u2013 Ful